{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784378073356,"sessionID":"ses_08acc7a6affeS35KntG0P1wx2Z","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_MUxVkwARsm8l6WCpxhTrSEYt","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"design-interface|design-foundations|design-motion|design-audit|open-design|hub|cost|integration","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Evidence-backed strategy for indexing, retrieving, and consuming the 1,290-style design-token corpus across the sk-design hub and five modes.\"\n\n  Line 21: This design wins on leverage versus cost because it preserves deterministic eligibility and freshness, adds lexical recall where measured evidence supports it, bounds context to approximately 1 KB of cards plus mode-proportional hydration, and keeps taste with the modes. The minimum viable layer is estimated at 5-8 engineer-days. A disposable FTS5 accelerator adds approximately 1-2 days. Semantic reranking is not a baseline dependency; it remains an optional later ablation only if a larger frozen human-labeled holdout proves incremental lift. [SOURCE: iterations/iteration-006.md:9-31] [SOURCE: iterations/iteration-007.md:15-28] [SOURCE: iterations/iteration-008.md:54-69]\n\n  Line 29: 1. Which retrieval substrate best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n\n  Line 30: 2. What should the hub and each mode consume, and when should the workflow use one coherent real style versus synthesize across several?\n\n  Line 33: 5. How should strategies rank by leverage versus cost after size, staleness, license, provenance, and fidelity risks?\n\n  Line 35: The loop performed eight evidence iterations. It inspected the sk-design hub and all five mode contracts, corpus artifacts and capture tooling, repository-native manifest/hash/SQLite patterns, representative and corpus-wide style data, and three pinned ranking experiments. It did not implement any retrieval system or modify the corpus. [SOURCE: deep-research-dashboard.md:30-56]\n\n  Line 147: The hub stays routing-only. The query layer exposes generic capabilities and evidence; each mode decides taste and selection through its existing contract. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-184] [SOURCE: iterations/iteration-006.md:17-17]\n\n  Line 259: ### Retrieval and context costs\n\n  Line 299: | 6 | Default full-corpus or full-document prompt loading | 2 | 0-1 day initial, very high recurring context cost | 1 | 3 | 1 | 5 | Reject |\n\n  Line 322: | Semantic-only or baseline-required semantic ranking | No same-generation measured lift; weakens determinism and increases cost | No verified corpus semantic index | 2, 3, 6, 7, 8 |\n\n  Line 332: | Default full-corpus prompt loading | Hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses provenance/coherence gates | Cost and risk ranking | 7 |\n\n  Line 361: | Mode authority drift | Keep hub/query capabilities generic; mode owns selection and taste | Reject retrieval result that changes routing or proof authority |\n\n  Line 398: - promote only if lift justifies dependency, versioning, and rebuild cost.\n\n  Line 406: - `iterations/iteration-003.md`: first ranking and context-cost ablation.\n\n  Line 416: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md`\n\n  Line 417: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md`\n\n  Line 418: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md`\n\n  Line 419: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:\n  Line 18: Focus Area: Relevance and context-cost validation for the proposed layered substrate.\n\n  Line 20: - Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n\n  Line 21: - What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n\n  Line 24: - How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:\n  Line 5: Investigate how the existing sk-design family can exploit its large corpus of extracted real-world styles without turning retrieval into generic averaging or imposing excessive runtime and maintenance cost.\n\n  Line 9: How should the sk-design hub and the interface, foundations, motion, audit, and md-generator modes index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style corpus under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/`?\n\n  Line 13: - [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n\n  Line 14: - [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n\n  Line 17: - [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n  Line 23: - Do not implement an index, query service, or mode integration.\n\n  Line 30: - A legal stop requires evidence-backed answers for all five key questions, source diversity across sk-design contracts and corpus samples, and a ranked strategy table with concrete costs and risks.\n\n  Line 34: - Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n\n  Line 35: - What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n\n  Line 38: - How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n  Line 46: - scanning every surfaced provenance record and extraction bundle converted a representative license concern into a qualified corpus-wide metadata result, while reusing iteration 6's component measurements kept cost estimates tied to repository evidence. (iteration 7)\n\n  Line 116: ### Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n\n  Line 117: - What was tried: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n\n  Line 119: - Do NOT retry: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n\n  Line 141: ### Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n\n  Line 142: - What was tried: Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction.\n\n  Line 144: - Do NOT retry: Letting corpus rank over