{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784379021269,"sessionID":"ses_08acc7a6affeS35KntG0P1wx2Z","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_HIVlNDTELudxBhV1EKUPPXa5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"^- \\[[ x]\\]|^## 11\\. NEXT FOCUS|^How should|^## 6\\. ANSWERED|^- What hub|^- How should","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"Found 27 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:\n  Line 15: How should the 1,290-style design-token library at `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/` be utilized globally across the sk-design hub and its non-md-generator modes plus `design-mcp-open-design`, with per-mode integration shapes, out-of-the-box extensions, and rough build costs?\n\n  Line 19: - [x] What hub-level contract can expose corpus capabilities, task-derived queries, authority order, and proof requirements while keeping the hub routing-only?\n\n  Line 20: - [ ] How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a style chooser or copy path?\n\n  Line 21: - [ ] How should `design-foundations` turn captured token axes and relationships into safe starting systems, compatibility maps, and implementation-ready evidence without averaging values or claiming accessibility proof?\n\n  Line 22: - [ ] How should `design-motion` discover and use sparse temporal evidence, infer no motion from static styles safely, and build motion-specific exemplars or negative baselines under its restraint gate?\n\n  Line 23: - [ ] How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost?\n\n  Line 43: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n\n  Line 44: - What hub-level contract can expose corpus capabilities, task-derived queries, authority order, and proof requirements while keeping the hub routing-only?\n\n  Line 133: - How should `design-interface` use coherent exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path? (iteration 1)\n\n  Line 134: - How should `design-foundations` turn token axes and relationships into safe starting systems and compatibility maps without averaging or false proof? (iteration 1)\n\n  Line 135: - How should `design-motion` use sparse temporal evidence and safe no-motion inference under its restraint gate? (iteration 1)\n\n  Line 136: - How should `design-audit` and Open Design operationalize drift, similarity, provenance, and transport grounding, and what should ship first after contract validation? (iteration 1)\n\n  Line 137: - How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path? (iteration 2)\n\n  Line 142: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n\n  Line 143: How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-001.md:\n  Line 47: - What hub-level contract can expose corpus capabilities, task-derived queries, authority order, and proof requirements while keeping the hub routing-only? Answer: `CORPUS_CONTEXT_PLAN v1`, with neutral capability disclosure at intake, mode-owned request/selection after routing, and hub-rendered authority/proof/fallback fields.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:\n  Line 30: - How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost? Answer: use `AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` as a non-authoritative comparison lane and `OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` as a generation-bound, no-cache, mandatory-pairing handshake with return reconciliation; ship audit schema/fixtures, then drift validation, then receipt validation, then live transport plumbing.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-dashboard.md:\n  Line 46: - [x] What hub-level contract can expose corpus capabilities, task-derived queries, authority order, and proof requirements while keeping the hub routing-only?\n\n  Line 47: - [ ] How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a style chooser or copy path? [legacy-import]\n\n  Line 48: - [ ] How should `design-foundations` turn captured token axes and relationships into safe starting systems, compatibility maps, and implementation-ready evidence without averaging values or claiming accessibility proof? [legacy-import]\n\n  Line 49: - [ ] How should `design-motion` discover and use sparse temporal evidence, infer no motion from static styles safely, and build motion-specific exemplars or negative baselines under its restraint gate? [legacy-import]\n\n  Line 50: - [ ] How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost? [legacy-import]\n\n  Line 56: - [ ] How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a style chooser or copy path?\n\n  Line 57: - [ ] How should `design-foundations` turn captured token axes and relationships into safe starting systems, compatibility maps, and implementation-ready evidence without averaging values or claiming accessibility proof?\n\n  Line 58: - [ ] How should `design-motion` discover and use sparse temporal evidence, infer no motion from static styles safely, and build motion-specific exemplars or negative baselines under its restraint gate?\n\n  Line 59: - [ ] How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost?\n\n  Line 98: How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path?\n","metadata":{"matches":27,"truncated":false},"title":"^- \\[[ x]\\]|^## 11\\. NEXT FOCUS|^How should|^## 6\\. ANSWERED|^- What hub|^- How should","time":{"start":1784379021257,"end":1784379021268}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d106ba09716cee4016a5b768d36948191aa9414824d060234"}},"id":"prt_f754717af001FQO57TTMVW5SPc","sessionID":"ses_08acc7a6affeS35KntG0P1wx2Z","messageID":"msg_f7546c5ce001tVoFgSp4r7D05e"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784379021321,"sessionID":"ses_08acc7a6affeS35KntG0P1wx2Z","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_56qa9zS5zPZE8bZI9L2a53K1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 2: Audit Comparison and Open Design Transport Contracts\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Define complete, mode-safe contracts for (1) corpus-relative drift, similarity, and provenance evidence inside `design-audit` and (2) corpus-grounded live reads and runs through the Open Design transport. The scope is contract validation and ship order, not implementation or live Open Design execution. The corpus remains comparison/reference evidence; target evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, severity, judgment, and remediation ownership remain separate authorities.\n6: \n7: ## Actions Taken\n8: \n9: 1. Reused phase 001's generation-bound cards, mode-owned selection, audit hydration cap, provenance, anti-copy, and proof constraints rather than reopening retrieval architecture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:96-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191]\n10: 2. Inspected audit target resolution, evidence strength, deterministic-scan boundaries, severity, scoring, worksheet carry-through, report ordering, anti-pattern/token-drift checks, and accepted-finding handoff. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:83-117] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-138] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-79]\n11: 3. Tested an audit comparison lane against four deliberately distinct evidence classes: authoritative target evidence, corpus comparison evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, and severity/remediation decisions. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:56-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [INFERENCE: a separate lane is necessary because the existing contracts assign different proof powers to these classes]\n12: 4. Inspected Open Design's mandatory pairing, guarded design-bearing reads, no-cache rule, multi-turn run, live tool verification, parity check, and generated-output boundary; no Open Design tool or run was invoked. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:38-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:22-45]\n13: \n14: ## Findings\n15: \n16: 1. **`AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` should be a separate worksheet/report lane, not another target-evidence type.** Its input is `{target, intendedAnchor?, comparisonPurpose, corpusGeneration, references[]}`. Every reference carries only style id, artifact/content hash, provenance, rights/use label, selected axes, and selection rationale. Each comparison row records `{axis, targetObservation, referenceObservation, relation: aligned|intentional-delta|unexplained-drift|comparison-unavailable, evidenceLabel, limitation}`. An intended anchor may support a drift finding only when the target's owned system or brief names it; otherwise corpus distribution or nearest references are contextual observations, not defects. This preserves the current requirement to resolve one stable target and keep source/render/design-artifact evidence legible while adding the phase-001 intended-anchor-plus-one-contrast comparison cap. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:134-145] [INFERENCE: schema fields operationalize the cited authority and hydration constraints]\n17: \n18: 2. **Corpus comparison can inform a finding, but it cannot supply severity, accessibility/performance proof, or remediation authority.** Severity continues to derive from target-observed user impact; a corpus comparison may explain systemic token drift, anti-default prevalence, or an unexplained departure from an intended anchor, but similarity alone cannot raise P0-P3 or any `/20` score. Accessibility retains its seven-layer coverage matrix, and performance above 2 still needs a named numeric metric or explicit `not-assessed`; corpus values prove neither. A resulting accepted finding keeps its confirmed/inferred caveat and routes to `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, and ultimately `sk-code` through the existing backlog card—the audit still never fixes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-146] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md:49-67] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-99]\n19: \n20: 3. **`OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` should be the mandatory design-bearing handshake.** Before a guarded read or run, the paired judgment mode emits `{pairedMode, skDesignGateProof, purpose, targetProjectOrSystem, corpusGeneration, selectedReferences[], allowedInfluenceAxes, prohibitedReuse, briefDigest, noCache:true}`. `selectedReferences` contains IDs, hashes, provenance/use labels, and mode-owned rationale—not `DESIGN.md`, token, component, screenshot, or Open Design payload bytes. The transport then (a) confirms the daemon, (b) verifies live `tools/list`, (c) revalidates the corpus generation before any hydration, (d) reads any Open Design system live, and (e) passes only mode-owned, transformed constraints into the brief and discovery answers. A generation mismatch blocks the design-bearing call until the mode re-queries/reselects and supersedes the receipt; it never silently uses stale evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:60-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:130-132] [INFERENCE: the receipt binds the existing pairing/no-cache gates to phase-001 generation refusal]\n21: \n22: 4. **The return path must reconcile transport output back to judgment and proof rather than treating a completed run as acceptance.** The receipt is extended after the multi-turn build with `{projectId, conversationId, runIds, entryFile, previewUrl, returnedArtifactHashes, liveReadAt, toolSurfaceEvidence}`. The paired mode inspects the live preview/artifacts, classifies each allowed influence as `applied|modified-for-target|rejected`, records target evidence and residual gaps, then attaches that reconciliation to `CORPUS_USE_PROOF v1` and the normal mode handoff. `awaiting_input`, zero files, missing preview/artifact proof, a changed corpus generation, or an unreconciled design delta remains incomplete. Open Design owns transport facts only; the paired mode owns parity and acceptance, while audit may later evaluate the built target. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:30-45] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:154-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [INFERENCE: reconciliation joins transport provenance to the existing application-proof gate without granting transport judgment]\n23: \n24: 5. **Ship order should validate the audit lane before live transport integration.** Ranked by leverage, cost, and dependency: (1) audit worksheet/report schema plus fixtures for intended-anchor, no-anchor, generation-mismatch, and unavailable-comparison cases—high leverage, small cost (2-4 engineer-days); (2) deterministic per-axis drift fingerprint and provenance validator—high leverage, medium cost (4-7 days), but only after schema fixtures prevent scalar-score authority; (3) Open Design receipt schema plus offline generation/no-cache/pairing validators—high leverage, small-medium cost (3-5 days); (4) live read/run receipt plumbing and return reconciliation—medium-high leverage, medium cost (5-8 days) and last because it depends on the settled receipt and a running external daemon. This refines iteration 1's envelope-first/audit-before-transport sequence with executable contract slices. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:38-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:34-45] [INFERENCE: ordering minimizes schema rework and defers the external-daemon dependency]\n25: \n26: 6. **Unsafe similarity, copying, and transport-authority paths are contract failures, not optional cautions.** Reject a nearest-neighbor or scalar “genericness” score as proof of poor quality or copying; reject exact token/motif transfer based only on proximity or attribution; reject raw corpus/Open Design payload caching; reject stale-generation fallback; reject one-shot `start_run` completion; reject transport-selected style, transport-issued acceptance, and automatic remediation. Similarity may be a reproducible descriptive observation with named axes and limitations, but copying requires independent evidence and quality remains target- and mode-judged. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-364] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:48-58] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:34-45]\n27: \n28: ## Questions Answered\n29: \n30: - How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost? Answer: use `AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` as a non-authoritative comparison lane and `OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` as a generation-bound, no-cache, mandatory-pairing handshake with return reconciliation; ship audit schema/fixtures, then drift validation, then receipt validation, then live transport plumbing.\n31: \n32: ## Questions Remaining\n33: \n34: 1. How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path?\n35: 2. How should `design-foundations` turn token axes and relationships into safe starting systems and compatibility maps without averaging or false proof?\n36: 3. How should `design-motion` use sparse temporal evidence and safe no-motion inference under its restraint gate?\n37: \n38: ## Dead Ends\n39: \n40: - **Similarity as severity, quality, or copying proof:** nearest-neighbor distance and corpus prevalence lack target impact and independent copying evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-45] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191]\n41: - **Raw exact-value or signature-motif transfer:** provenance does not authorize copying, and phase 001 forbids unreviewed source-specific reuse under unknown rights. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-356]\n42: - **Transport authority or one-shot completion:** Open Design is transport-only, and turn 1 yields a discovery form with zero files. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:48-54] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:154-170]\n43: - **Cached or stale payload fallback:** design content stays live, while corpus hydration refuses generation mismatch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-150] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:130-132]\n44: \n45: ## Assessment\n46: \n47: - New information ratio: 0.92\n48: - Novelty calculation: 5 of 6 findings are fully new operational contracts or sequencing details and 1 partially refines iteration 1's risk boundaries: `(5 + 0.5 × 1) / 6 = 0.92`.\n49: - Questions addressed: the combined audit/Open Design key question.\n50: - Questions answered: 1 this iteration; 2 of 5 cumulatively.\n51: - Edge cases: none. No source contradiction was found; generation mismatch, missing live evidence, and unfinished runs are explicit contract failure states rather than encountered dependencies because this iteration was required to inspect checked-in contracts only.\n52: \n53: ## Reflection\n54: \n55: - What worked and why: separating target, comparison, deterministic proof, and transport evidence before designing schemas prevented corpus similarity from leaking into severity or transport acceptance.\n56: - What did not work and why: a single shared “provenance receipt” was too coarse; audit needs comparison semantics while Open Design needs a temporal pre-call/post-run handshake, so one record would blur authority and lifecycle.\n57: - What I would do differently: validate the two schemas with frozen positive and negative fixtures before connecting either to live tooling; this would make generation mismatch, no-anchor comparison, and incomplete-run failures mechanically reviewable.\n58: \n59: ## Sources Consulted\n60: \n61: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:96-191`\n62: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-364`\n63: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:85-173`\n64: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-135`\n65: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-138`\n66: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md:38-127`\n67: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80`\n68: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-181`\n69: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-99`\n70: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154`\n71: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:38-170`\n72: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:22-45`\n73: \n74: ## Recommended Next Focus\n75: \n76: Define and fixture-test `design-interface`'s relational exemplar contract: anchor, deliberate contrast, rejected default, transformation delta, anti-copy boundary, variation-diversity behavior, and exact context/proof/handoff fields.\n\n(End of file - total 76 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 2: Audit Comparison and Open Design Transport Contracts\n\n## Focus\n\nDefine complete, mode-safe contracts for (1) corpus-relative drift, similarity, and provenance evidence inside `design-audit` and (2) corpus-grounded live reads and runs through the Open Design transport. The scope is contract validation and ship order, not implementation or live Open Design execution. The corpus remains comparison/reference evidence; target evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, severity, judgment, and remediation ownership remain separate authorities.\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. Reused phase 001's generation-bound cards, mode-owned selection, audit hydration cap, provenance, anti-copy, and proof constraints rather than reopening retrieval architecture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:96-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191]\n2. Inspected audit target resolution, evidence strength, deterministic-scan boundaries, severity, scoring, worksheet carry-through, report ordering, anti-pattern/token-drift checks, and accepted-finding handoff. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:83-117] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-138] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-79]\n3. Tested an audit comparison lane against four deliberately distinct evidence classes: authoritative target evidence, corpus comparison evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, and severity/remediation decisions. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:56-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [INFERENCE: a separate lane is necessary because the existing contracts assign different proof powers to these classes]\n4. Inspected Open Design's mandatory pairing, guarded design-bearing reads, no-cache rule, multi-turn run, live tool verification, parity check, and generated-output boundary; no Open Design tool or run was invoked. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:38-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:22-45]\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **`AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` should be a separate worksheet/report lane, not another target-evidence type.** Its input is `{target, intendedAnchor?, comparisonPurpose, corpusGeneration, references[]}`. Every reference carries only style id, artifact/content hash, provenance, rights/use label, selected axes, and selection rationale. Each comparison row records `{axis, targetObservation, referenceObservation, relation: aligned|intentional-delta|unexplained-drift|comparison-unavailable, evidenceLabel, limitation}`. An intended anchor may support a drift finding only when the target's owned system or brief names it; otherwise corpus distribution or nearest references are contextual observations, not defects. This preserves the current requirement to resolve one stable target and keep source/render/design-artifact evidence legible while adding the phase-001 intended-anchor-plus-one-contrast comparison cap. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:134-145] [INFERENCE: schema fields operationalize the cited authority and hydration constraints]\n\n2. **Corpus comparison can inform a finding, but it cannot supply severity, accessibility/performance proof, or remediation authority.** Severity continues to derive from target-observed user impact; a corpus comparison may explain systemic token drift, anti-default prevalence, or an unexplained departure from an intended anchor, but similarity alone cannot raise P0-P3 or any `/20` score. Accessibility retains its seven-layer coverage matrix, and performance above 2 still needs a named numeric metric or explicit `not-assessed`; corpus values prove neither. A resulting accepted finding keeps its confirmed/inferred caveat and routes to `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, and ultimately `sk-code` through the existing backlog card—the audit still never fixes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-146] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md:49-67] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-99]\n\n3. **`OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` should be the mandatory design-bearing handshake.** Before a guarded read or run, the paired judgment mode emits `{pairedMode, skDesignGateProof, purpose, targetProjectOrSystem, corpusGeneration, selectedReferences[], allowedInfluenceAxes, prohibitedReuse, briefDigest, noCache:true}`. `selectedReferences` contains IDs, hashes, provenance/use labels, and mode-owned rationale—not `DESIGN.md`, token, component, screenshot, or Open Design payload bytes. The transport then (a) confirms the daemon, (b) verifies live `tools/list`, (c) revalidates the corpus generation before any hydration, (d) reads any Open Design system live, and (e) passes only mode-owned, transformed constraints into the brief and discovery answers. A generation mismatch blocks the design-bearing call until the mode re-queries/reselects and supersedes the receipt; it never silently uses stale evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:60-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:130-132] [INFERENCE: the receipt binds the existing pairing/no-cache gates to phase-001 generation refusal]","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md","text":"# Iteration 2: Audit Comparison and Open Design Transport Contracts\n\n## Focus\n\nDefine complete, mode-safe contracts for (1) corpus-relative drift, similarity, and provenance evidence inside `design-audit` and (2) corpus-grounded live reads and runs through the Open Design transport. The scope is contract validation and ship order, not implementation or live Open Design execution. The corpus remains comparison/reference evidence; target evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, severity, judgment, and remediation ownership remain separate authorities.\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. Reused phase 001's generation-bound cards, mode-owned selection, audit hydration cap, provenance, anti-copy, and proof constraints rather than reopening retrieval architecture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:96-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191]\n2. Inspected audit target resolution, evidence strength, deterministic-scan boundaries, severity, scoring, worksheet carry-through, report ordering, anti-pattern/token-drift checks, and accepted-finding handoff. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:83-117] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-138] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-181] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-79]\n3. Tested an audit comparison lane against four deliberately distinct evidence classes: authoritative target evidence, corpus comparison evidence, deterministic accessibility/performance proof, and severity/remediation decisions. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:56-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [INFERENCE: a separate lane is necessary because the existing contracts assign different proof powers to these classes]\n4. Inspected Open Design's mandatory pairing, guarded design-bearing reads, no-cache rule, multi-turn run, live tool verification, parity check, and generated-output boundary; no Open Design tool or run was invoked. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:38-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:22-45]\n\n## Findings\n\n1. **`AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` should be a separate worksheet/report lane, not another target-evidence type.** Its input is `{target, intendedAnchor?, comparisonPurpose, corpusGeneration, references[]}`. Every reference carries only style id, artifact/content hash, provenance, rights/use label, selected axes, and selection rationale. Each comparison row records `{axis, targetObservation, referenceObservation, relation: aligned|intentional-delta|unexplained-drift|comparison-unavailable, evidenceLabel, limitation}`. An intended anchor may support a drift finding only when the target's owned system or brief names it; otherwise corpus distribution or nearest references are contextual observations, not defects. This preserves the current requirement to resolve one stable target and keep source/render/design-artifact evidence legible while adding the phase-001 intended-anchor-plus-one-contrast comparison cap. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:134-145] [INFERENCE: schema fields operationalize the cited authority and hydration constraints]\n\n2. **Corpus comparison can inform a finding, but it cannot supply severity, accessibility/performance proof, or remediation authority.** Severity continues to derive from target-observed user impact; a corpus comparison may explain systemic token drift, anti-default prevalence, or an unexplained departure from an intended anchor, but similarity alone cannot raise P0-P3 or any `/20` score. Accessibility retains its seven-layer coverage matrix, and performance above 2 still needs a named numeric metric or explicit `not-assessed`; corpus values prove neither. A resulting accepted finding keeps its confirmed/inferred caveat and routes to `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, and ultimately `sk-code` through the existing backlog card—the audit still never fixes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-97] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-146] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md:49-67] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-99]\n\n3. **`OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` should be the mandatory design-bearing handshake.** Before a guarded read or run, the paired judgment mode emits `{pairedMode, skDesignGateProof, purpose, targetProjectOrSystem, corpusGeneration, selectedReferences[], allowedInfluenceAxes, prohibitedReuse, briefDigest, noCache:true}`. `selectedReferences` contains IDs, hashes, provenance/use labels, and mode-owned rationale—not `DESIGN.md`, token, component, screenshot, or Open Design payload bytes. The transport then (a) confirms the daemon, (b) verifies live `tools/list`, (c) revalidates the corpus generation before any hydration, (d) reads any Open Design system live, and (e) passes only mode-owned, transformed constraints into the brief and discovery answers. A generation mismatch blocks the design-bearing call until the mode re-queries/reselects and supersedes the receipt; it never silently uses stale evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:60-98] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:130-132] [INFERENCE: the receipt binds the existing pairing/no-cache gates to phase-001 generation refusal]\n\n4. **The return path must reconcile transport output back to judgment and proof rather than treating a completed run as acceptance.** The receipt is extended after the multi-turn build with `{projectId, conversationId, runIds, entryFile, previewUrl, returnedArtifactHashes, liveReadAt, toolSurfaceEvidence}`. The paired mode inspects the live preview/artifacts, classifies each allowed influence as `applied|modified-for-target|rejected`, records target evidence and residual gaps, then attaches that reconciliation to `CORPUS_USE_PROOF v1` and the normal mode handoff. `awaiting_input`, zero files, missing preview/artifact proof, a changed corpus generation, or an unreconciled design delta remains incomplete. Open Design owns transport facts only; the paired mode owns parity and acceptance, while audit may later evaluate the built target. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:30-45] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:154-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [INFERENCE: reconciliation joins transport provenance to the existing application-proof gate without granting transport judgment]\n\n5. **Ship order should validate the audit lane before live transport integration.** Ranked by leverage, cost, and dependency: (1) audit worksheet/report schema plus fixtures for intended-anchor, no-anchor, generation-mismatch, and unavailable-comparison cases—high leverage, small cost (2-4 engineer-days); (2) deterministic per-axis drift fingerprint and provenance validator—high leverage, medium cost (4-7 days), but only after schema fixtures prevent scalar-score authority; (3) Open Design receipt schema plus offline generation/no-cache/pairing validators—high leverage, small-medium cost (3-5 days); (4) live read/run receipt plumbing and return reconciliation—medium-high leverage, medium cost (5-8 days) and last because it depends on the settled receipt and a running external daemon. This refines iteration 1's envelope-first/audit-before-transport sequence with executable contract slices. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:38-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-170] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:34-45] [INFERENCE: ordering minimizes schema rework and defers the external-daemon dependency]\n\n6. **Unsafe similarity, copying, and transport-authority paths are contract failures, not optional cautions.** Reject a nearest-neighbor or scalar “genericness” score as proof of poor quality or copying; reject exact token/motif transfer based only on proximity or attribution; reject raw corpus/Open Design payload caching; reject stale-generation fallback; reject one-shot `start_run` completion; reject transport-selected style, transport-issued acceptance, and automatic remediation. Similarity may be a reproducible descriptive observation with named axes and limitations, but copying requires independent evidence and quality remains target- and mode-judged. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-364] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:48-58] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:34-45]\n\n## Questions Answered\n\n- How should `design-audit` and `design-mcp-open-design` use the corpus for drift, similarity, provenance, comparison, and transport grounding; which cross-mode ideas should ship first at what rough cost? Answer: use `AUDIT_CORPUS_COMPARISON v1` as a non-authoritative comparison lane and `OPEN_DESIGN_GROUNDING_RECEIPT v1` as a generation-bound, no-cache, mandatory-pairing handshake with return reconciliation; ship audit schema/fixtures, then drift validation, then receipt validation, then live transport plumbing.\n\n## Questions Remaining\n\n1. How should `design-interface` use coherent style exemplars for grounding, anti-default critique, variation diversity, and handoff without becoming a chooser or copy path?\n2. How should `design-foundations` turn token axes and relationships into safe starting systems and compatibility maps without averaging or false proof?\n3. How should `design-motion` use sparse temporal evidence and safe no-motion inference under its restraint gate?\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- **Similarity as severity, quality, or copying proof:** nearest-neighbor distance and corpus prevalence lack target impact and independent copying evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-45] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191]\n- **Raw exact-value or signature-motif transfer:** provenance does not authorize copying, and phase 001 forbids unreviewed source-specific reuse under unknown rights. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:172-191] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-356]\n- **Transport authority or one-shot completion:** Open Design is transport-only, and turn 1 yields a discovery form with zero files. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:48-54] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:154-170]\n- **Cached or stale payload fallback:** design content stays live, while corpus hydration refuses generation mismatch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:143-150] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:130-132]\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 0.92\n- Novelty calculation: 5 of 6 findings are fully new operational contracts or sequencing details and 1 partially refines iteration 1's risk boundaries: `(5 + 0.5 × 1) / 6 = 0.92`.\n- Questions addressed: the combined audit/Open Design key question.\n- Questions answered: 1 this iteration; 2 of 5 cumulatively.\n- Edge cases: none. No source contradiction was found; generation mismatch, missing live evidence, and unfinished runs are explicit contract failure states rather than encountered dependencies because this iteration was required to inspect checked-in contracts only.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: separating target, comparison, deterministic proof, and transport evidence before designing schemas prevented corpus similarity from leaking into severity or transport acceptance.\n- What did not work and why: a single shared “provenance receipt” was too coarse; audit needs comparison semantics while Open Design needs a temporal pre-call/post-run handshake, so one record would blur authority and lifecycle.\n- What I would do differently: validate the two schemas with frozen positive and negative fixtures before connecting either to live tooling; this would make generation mismatch, no-anchor comparison, and incomplete-run failures mechanically reviewable.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:96-191`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/research.md:350-364`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:85-173`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/evidence_capture.md:40-135`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit_contract.md:36-138`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti_patterns_production.md:38-127`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_evidence_worksheet.md:29-80`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit_report_template.md:116-181`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/sk_code_handoff.md:71-99`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/SKILL.md:125-154`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/tool_surface.md:38-170`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-mcp-open-design/references/design_parity_transport.md:22-45`\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nDefine and fixture-test `design-interface`'s relational exemplar contract: anchor, deliberate contrast, rejected default, transformation delta, anti-copy boundary, variation-diversity behavior, and exact context/proof/handoff fields.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":76,"totalLines":76,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/003-global-modes-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md","time":{"start":1784379021315,"end":1784379021319}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0d106ba09716cee4016a5b768d36a481918fb33101c3948cc7"}},"id":"prt_f754717ca001aCkM0RXyyiyUVe","sessionID":"ses_08acc7a6affeS35KntG0P1wx2Z","messageID":"msg_f7546c5ce001tVoFgSp4r7D05e"}}
